<command:command xmlns:maml="http://schemas.microsoft.com/maml/2004/10" xmlns:command="http://schemas.microsoft.com/maml/dev/command/2004/10" xmlns:dev="http://schemas.microsoft.com/maml/dev/2004/10">
<command:details>
<command:name>Edit-FarMacro</command:name>
<maml:description>
<maml:para>Opens the editor with the macro sequence and install the macro on saving if its syntax is correct.</maml:para>
</maml:description>
<command:verb>Edit</command:verb>
<command:noun>FarMacro</command:noun>
</command:details>
<maml:description>
<maml:para>Opens the editor with the macro sequence. Syntax highlighting should work if the Colorer plugin is used. On saving, if syntax is valid, the macro is installed and ready to use. On syntax errors an error message is shown and the cursor is set to the error position. On exit, if syntax is not valid, you are prompted to continue or discard the changes. NOTE: in this way you only edit the sequence, other macro options remains default for a new macro and not changed for an existing.

There are three modes depending on parameter sets:</maml:para>
<maml:para></maml:para>
<maml:para>&gt; Edit-FarMacro [-FilePath] [-Panel]</maml:para>
<maml:para>Based on an existing or a new macro file. It simply edits the file and checks syntax on saving.</maml:para>
<maml:para></maml:para>
<maml:para>&gt; Edit-FarMacro [-Macro] [-Panel]</maml:para>
<maml:para>Based on a macro object.</maml:para>
<maml:para></maml:para>
<maml:para>&gt; Edit-FarMacro -Name [-Area] [-Panel]</maml:para>
<maml:para>Based on an existing or a new macro specified by names.</maml:para>
</maml:description>
<command:syntax>
<command:syntaxItem>
<maml:name>Edit-FarMacro</maml:name>
<command:parameter required="false" position="named" >
<maml:name>FilePath</maml:name>
<command:parameterValue required="true">String</command:parameterValue>
</command:parameter>
<command:parameter required="false" position="named" >
<maml:name>Panel</maml:name>
<command:parameterValue required="true">Panel</command:parameterValue>
</command:parameter>
</command:syntaxItem>
